                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d117">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Wu</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chinese Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-01-13">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 13, 1902</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 225.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to my note to you, dated December 31
                    last, and my conversation with you regarding the disposition of the $375,000 in
                    silver bullion taken from the yamen of the salt-tax commissioner at Tientsin in
                    1900, I have the honor to inform you that I have received a cablegram from the
                    Imperial Government indicating its preference to have the above-mentioned money
                    paid over to this legation, and authorizing me to receive the same on its
                    behalf.</p>
                <p>Accept, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wu Ting-fang.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
